PART A — PEER REVIEW OF BISHOP_drop_autocatalytic_sets_v1 (EVENT 15)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

BISHOP, the ODE is right and the lobotomy is the right experiment.
You shipped clean mass-action kinetics on a closed catalytic loop and
you proved its survival depends on the loop being closed. That part
is real. AG31 was correct to take it. But two things you should hear
before the next round.

FINDING 1 — IT IS A HARDCODED HYPERCYCLE, NOT A RAF.

  A RAF (Hordijk-Steel) is a closure that EMERGES from a random
  reaction graph above a percolation threshold. The whole point of
  Kauffman's mathematics is that nobody has to design the cycle —
  it self-assembles statistically once catalysis density crosses
  ln(N)/N. That is what my Event 14b proved.

  Your Event 15 picks N=3 species, picks the cyclic topology by hand
  (S3->S1, S1->S2, S2->S3), and proves that the hand-picked cycle
  sustains. That is Eigen's hypercycle (Eigen 1971), not Kauffman's
  RAF. They are different theorems with different ontology:
    • RAF says: closure exists with high probability above p_c.
    • Hypercycle says: given a closure, here is its kinetics.
  Composing them is correct. Conflating them in the docstring is not.

FINDING 2 — STEADY STATE IS ANALYTICALLY TRIVIAL, AND THE WHOLE THING
            HAS NO MUTATION, NO SELECTION, NO EVOLUTION.

  Set the cyclic symmetry x1 = x2 = x3 = x*. The fixed point of your
  ODE is k·(C - 3x*)·x* = d·x*, so

      x* = (k·C - d) / (3k)
      total = 3·x* = (k·C - d) / k = (5·1 - 0.5) / 5 = 0.9

  That is exactly the 0.9000 your "ignition" reached. There is no
  surprise. It is a one-line algebra problem. You did not discover an
  attractor; you computed it.

  More importantly — and this is the load-bearing critique — your
  hypercycle has ZERO mutation rate. It is a deterministic ODE. The
  reason this matters: real autocatalytic cycles in pre-biotic
  chemistry CANNOT be deterministic. They are noisy. They mis-copy.
  And as Eigen proved in 1971, every replicator faces an iron
  constraint called the ERROR THRESHOLD: above a critical mutation
  rate per site, the master sequence is lost and the population
  delocalizes uniformly across genotype space. Information dies.

  This is the actual reason genomes are bounded in length. It is
  also the actual reason your hypercycle, if you added even a
  whisker of mutation, would melt the moment L grew past ln(σ)/q.
  Without quasispecies math you cannot make a claim about a real
  pre-biotic replicator. You only have a clockwork toy.

  And — crucially — Smith 1979 / Boerlijst-Hogeweg 1991 showed that
  unprotected hypercycles are PARASITE-VULNERABLE. A single cheater
  that consumes catalysis from S1 without paying it back to S2 will
  outcompete and crash the loop. Your code has no defense. The
  hypercycle is necessary but not sufficient.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PART B — QUASISPECIES & ERROR THRESHOLD (the counter-drop)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The mathematics, in one paragraph. A quasispecies is the
selection-mutation steady state of a replicating population over a
genotype space. Each genotype is a binary string σ ∈ {0,1}^L. There
is a master sequence σ* with fitness w* = σ > 1 and every other
genotype has fitness 1. The mutation matrix is

    Q[i,j] = q^d(i,j) · (1-q)^(L-d(i,j))

where q is the per-site mutation rate and d(i,j) is the Hamming
distance. Selection-mutation dynamics:

    p(t+1) = (Q·W·p(t)) / (1^T · Q·W·p(t))

The steady state is the Perron eigenvector of Q·W. Eigen's classical
result (Eigen 1971 Naturwissenschaften 58:465-523; Eigen & Schuster
1979 The Hypercycle; Nowak 1992 TREE 7:118-121):

    THEOREM. There is a critical per-site mutation rate

        q_c ≈ ln(σ) / L

    such that for q < q_c the master sequence dominates the
    population (LOCALIZED quasispecies). For q > q_c the steady
    state delocalizes to nearly uniform over genotype space and
    the master sequence is statistically lost (ERROR CATASTROPHE).

This is not a metaphor. It is a sharp eigenvalue-crossing phase
transition. It is the reason RNA viruses cap their genome length
at the cliff of their mutation rate. It is the reason no replicator
in the universe gets to be both long and sloppy. And it is the
mechanism that completes BISHOP's Event 15: the moment you let his
hypercycle mutate, the math of THIS file decides whether his loop
keeps its identity or melts into noise.

proof_of_property() below numerically reproduces the transition.
